It is impossible to have a more striking instance of the declamatory style of Livy than we have here. His narrative is pitched in as plaintive a key as his report of speecheS. The remark at line 210, when the soldiers veil their resentment in presence of the disgrace of their leaders, is obviously an expression of what they ought to have done rather than a statement of what they did. In contrast to this M. Taine quotes the account in Thucydides, book iv, of the capitulation of Sphacteria. At the same time there is nothing false in Livy's flow of passion.
